explanation:
To decide whether OS_rename violates the MISRA guideline that pointers should be const-qualified when possible, the analyzer must inspect the declarations/definitions of all functions, types and objects that establish or consume pointer types in this function:

- OS_TranslatePath: need the prototype to confirm the parameter types (is the input path parameter declared as const char *?) and whether it accepts/needs a const pointer. If its parameter is non-const, passing a const-qualified argument may indicate a mismatch or missed opportunity to make it const.

- OS_FileRename_Impl: prototype required to determine whether its path parameters are declared const-qualified (const char *) or not; this affects whether OS_rename should or must pass const pointers or can further const-qualify local/argument pointers.

- OS_ObjectIdIterateActive: prototype needed to see how the iterator is initialized (does it take a pointer to a mutable iterator?) and whether any pointer parameters could be const-qualified.

- OS_ObjectIdIteratorGetNext: signature required to know whether it takes/returns pointers that should be const (e.g., does it accept a pointer-to-iterator as non-const) and whether it returns any pointer/token that influences constness decisions.

- OS_ObjectIdIteratorDestroy: prototype required to check whether it takes a pointer that must be mutable (non-const) or could accept a const pointer; relevant for determining whether the iterator type could/should be const-qualified.

- OS_object_iter_t: the iterator typedef/struct definition is needed to see its members and whether they are modified by iterator functions; this informs whether the local variable iter could be declared const or parts of it could be const-qualified.

- OS_stream_internal_record_t: the full struct definition is necessary to inspect the types of fields used here (particularly stream_name and socket_domain). You must know whether stream_name is a char array or char * and whether its type could or should be const-qualified in contexts where it is only read.

- OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET: macro or accessor function definition is required to know the type it yields (pointer to OS_stream_internal_record_t or pointer to const OS_stream_internal_record_t). That determines whether the returned pointer should be const-qualified at the call site in OS_rename.

- OS_stream_table: the declaration/type of the global object passed to OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET may affect the constness of the pointer returned by that macro/accessor; inspect its type to decide whether the table elements could be exposed as const.

- OS_SocketDomain_INVALID: the enum/constant and the type of socket_domain are needed to ensure the socket_domain comparison does not require mutating the stream record; if socket_domain is only read, that supports const qualification of the stream pointer in read-only contexts.

- strcmp: prototype from the C library (const char * parameters) must be checked to confirm that passing stream->stream_name (char * or char[] decayed) to a parameter declared as const is acceptable; it also shows whether the function expects const inputs (so stream_name could be const in contexts where only compared).

- strncpy: prototype is needed to confirm which parameter is const (strncpy(dest, src, n) has const char *src). Because OS_rename writes into stream->stream_name by calling strncpy(stream->stream_name, new, ...), the analyzer must check that this write is allowed and therefore whether stream (or stream_name) must remain non-const in this function.

- OS_MAX_LOCAL_PATH_LEN: definition of this macro (size) is useful to confirm that the local arrays old_path/new_path are correctly sized and to see if any pointer-to-array could be const-qualified (they are writable buffers here); it also helps confirm strncpy/OS_TranslatePath usage.

In short, these symbols together let the analyst determine (a) which pointers are only read and therefore could be const-qualified (parameters, returned table pointers, stream_name when only read), and (b) which pointers are actually written to (stream->stream_name via strncpy, local old_path/new_path buffers, iterator mutation) and therefore must remain non-const. Without these prototypes/definitions you cannot conclusively decide if additional const qualifiers are possible or required to comply with the MISRA rule.
